description.text:
This design provides a dual extruder compatible for Prusa i2 printer and Prusa i3 printer, by a system of bowden extrusion, to reduce the weight in the x-carriage and avoid vibrations during the print.
Each printer has a design for the x carriage. The rest of the pieces, are the same for both of them. The idea is to have the chance of changing easily your dual extruder from one printer to the other ( in case you have both models at home/work).

description.text: This is a small quadcopter using the innards of a Hubsan H107 (8.5mm diameter motors). The LEDs have been brought inboard and overall size reduced slightly.The weight is well under half that of the original shell.

Notes:

Easy print as long as first-layer adhesion is good. Frame weighs under 6g with 30% infill.

Wiring changes

First step is to unsolder the LED wiring and then solder the LEDs direct to the conveniently located pads on the PCB. Looking through the LED, the small electrodes go to the + pads.
Also remove the battery connector and reattach on the other side of the PCB. This will make assembly easier later.

Fitting the PCB to the frame.

Pass the motors through the holes in the frame ensuring they're dangling free. Loop back the battery connector trapping the wires between the frame cross-piece and PCB, then screw down the PCB using two of the original shell screws. Use a drop of cyanoacrylate or contact adhesive to attach the battery connector to the tab at the rear.

Inserting the motors.

There should be just enough length in the motor wire to take them beyond the motor mount, feed the wire into the slot and push the motor into the housing. Temporarily untwisting the lead will give a bit of extra length.
My motors were a perfect snug fit but as the results of a motor pulling out in a crash could be catastrophic I put a drop of thin cyanoacrylate at the top of the mount and let it wick down.
Prod the motor cables down into the channels and secure with the smallest blob of hot glue.

Battery mounting.

The battery mounts underneath using a small elastic band looped over the tabs on the topside. The captive battery connector eliminates strain on the PCB and gets rid of the dangly lead problem. Plug it in, power up and off you go!
(Don't forget the calibration - With drone flat, LHS stick to bottom right then wiggle RHS stick left and right until lights flash.)

A printable tiara, necklace, and earrings set for a Sailor Moon costume. They were designed at the last minute for a costume party the next day.
All parts were designed with Blender for printing on a Thing-O-Matic.

You'll need a few extra bits and pieces to complete the pieces, and the earrings require a little bit of basic jewellery making know-how, but nothing too complicated! Materials required:
  • Yellow PVA filament (or gold if you have some)
  • Elastic thread
  • Gold thread (or any light colour, I used a pale cream/yellow)
  • Length of red ribbon
  • 4 small gold beads
  • Red sharpie marker (or other make of permanent marker with small tip)
    • Necklace:
    This is the easiest bit, just print out the half moon and thread it onto a piece of red ribbon. Tie the ribbon at the back of your neck and you're done. Earrings:
    You'll need 4 small gold beads, some thread and two earring findings. Print two copies of the earring file and then string together the earring by first threading on the half moon, then the beads (using knots to keep them in the right place), then the earring findings. Tiara:
    A very useful feature of the coloured PVA is that it has a lower melting temperature to the regular plain plastic, and so you can mould the shape a bit after you take it off the build platform. That's how I got the tiara to fit exactly to my head. The trick is just to catch the plastic at the right moment where it's cool enough to touch comfortably, but still flexible. WARNING: Do not put on your head straight from the build surface! So to make the tiara, print out the file, take it off the build surface and allow to cool just enough then hold it in place on your forehead for a few seconds while it hardens. Tie some elastic thread through the holes to hold it onto your head. Then simple colour in the central oval with a red sharpie (you could also use air-fix paints, but a sharpie is much simpler and less messy). Hair:
    A quick additional on the hair. I used my own hair for the buns and clip-in extensions for the long pigtails. For the red circles in the hair I put red buttons on the end of a metal hair grips and pushed one into each bun. I had plenty of buttons so just painted two bright red with air-fix paints, but I do have a 3D-printable button you could use here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:13315

His Hitman can be found here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:66072 I've cut my Lara into pieces to help reduce the amount of supports needed and to make the prints cleaner and easier to paint. The pieces peg together and will stay put, but she comes apart easily if not glued together. If you don't want to fool around with the different pieces then I've included a file of her all fused together named LC-OnePiece.obj. I've included .x3g files that I used to print this (created for Replicator 2 with PLA filament). I've tried various ways to print the pieces and these files are the best combination that I've found. I've also included .objs if you want to set up the print files yourself or won't be printing in PLA. The body can print on its feet without supports and the left arm with the climbing hook seems to need a raft as well as supports enabled. The other parts only need supports. title: Star Wars: Legion Demo/Playtest Toolkit v0.2

description.text:
This set should have everything you need to playtest a game of Star Wars: Legion. You will need to provide miniatures (of course) and a set of 8-sided and 6-sided dice (I have 12 of each color).

I suggest you print the cards and place then in card sleeves with a regular card behind it. The dice stickers are scaled for dice that are 15mm to a side; scale appropriately for your personal dice. The order tokens have a unit symbol sticker that goes on the front side and a faction symbol sticker that goes on the back side. I used Avery opaque full-sheet shipping labels for printing my stickers.

The movement rulers print in two parts and just snap together -- they should still be free to move in the middle. The range rulers have a small built-in support piece for the peg; just snip that off after printing. You should not need support material for any of the 3D printed models.

The ruleset is current to what we know so far from demos and interviews. There are still four rules that are unknown. The ruleset published here has some proposed "house rules" to fill in those gaps. I will try to keep the rules document updated as we learn more.

Updates:
v0.2: Added references to rules found in JD's rules summary

description.text:
This is a focus mount that can be used on a telescope. It originates from a project I did with a school where we made an affordable telescope using parts from a DIY store and 3D printed parts. This focuser uses a large screw thread to provide the motion to move the eyepiece into focus, it needs to be rotated on it's axis, your printer will determine how accurate this is in terms of alignment. Like I said this was for a basic demonstration of a low-cost telescope. Print settings wise, 0.2mm resolution worked for me in PLA. The parts were printed separately and assembled with the large scale screw thread and M3 cap head screws. The adapter is modelled to suit a tune of 110mm diameter (standard UK soil pipe). The mount can be glued to a tube. Post printing it is necessary to clean the screw threads up with a file and work them together and apart again to make them run smoothly, a file and fine grade sandpaper are your friends here.

The focuser will accept a standard 1.25" eyepiece, again some sanding may be required to make it fit smoothly.

description.text:
Love your Ultimaker 3 but hate the poorly designed spool holder it came with? Then give this re-engineered spool holder a try!

UPDATE: Based on measurements from user jahnotto, the design has been updated and should fit an UM3 standard. This version has not been tested yet. You will not be able to use the cord cover (white metal piece that snaps on and covers the RFID cord) on the standard version.

NOTE: THIS DESIGN HAS NOT BEEN TESTED ON A STANDARD ULTIMAKER 3, IT HAS ONLY BEEN TESTED ON THE EXTENDED VERSION (UM3+). I am interested in hearing from anyone who is willing to test it on the standard size UM3. I have provided an image which shows the necessary clearance so you can measure before printing.

This spool holder was designed to address issues associated with the stock Ultimaker 3 spool holder. It is large enough to fit two 1 kg spools and can still be used with Ultimaker spools. It also completely rethinks the filament guide, making it far easier to use. No more taking it on and off to change spools and you can insert the filament into the guide after it has been loaded into the extruder.

Be sure to read "Print Settings" before printing (scaling is critical).

Read "Post-Printing" for assembly instructions and additional parts list.

This holder has been tested with MatterHackers and Hatchbox 1 kg spools and Ultimaker 0.35 kg spools.

Why I made this spool holder:
When it comes to 3D printers, Ultimaker has a reputation for making quality machines that work out of the box. But this is their first venture into dual extrusion, and it shows. Most of the issues are small annoyances; bugs that will be worked out. But the spool holder leaves a lot of room for improvement. The most common complaint is that you cannot fit two 1 kilogram spools of filament on it. The filament guide for that hooks onto the spool holder has a series of issues all by itself. It is awkward to use as it never wants to set right, it's too big for Ultimaker filament spools and too small for 1 kilogram spools, it hangs on the outside so you have to take it off everytime you change spools, and you have to make sure to thread the filament through it before feeding into the extruder. Forget to thread the filament and you have to unload the filament and start over.

Printer Brand:

Ultimaker

Printer:

Ultimaker 3 Extended

Resolution:

0.3

Infill:

30

Notes:

It is EXTREMELY important your printer be properly calibrated for this spool holder to work. Since it is for an Ultimaker 3 and you are likely printing with the UM, the most probable source of error is going to be shrinkage of material as it cools. Likely you will have to scale up the Z-axis (I had to do this on my printer). If you do not get the scaling correct, the RFID reader circuit board will not fit into the slot inside of the spool holder.

Additional Parts and Tools

Parts:
(7) M3 heat set inserts [McMaster-Carr part no. 94180A333]
(7) M3x8 screws [McMaster-Carr part no. 92000A118]
(7) M3 washers (optional) [McMaster-Carr part no. 93475A210]
Cyanoacrylate or other glue, epoxy, or bonding agent for the material you print with

Tools:

  • Screw driver
  • Soldering iron or another device to heat the heat-set inserts
  • Utility knife / box cutter
  • 2 mm drill bit
  • 2.8 or 2.9 mm drill bit, depending on your filament diameter (optional)
Step 1 - Heat Set Inserts

Use a soldering iron or similar to place the heat set inserts. Once they are set trim any plastic that bubbled up around the edges flush with the surface.

Spool Holder (5)

  • 4 go into the underside of the spool holder top and are used for screwing together the two halves of the spool holder.
  • 1 goes into the top near the rear and is used to hold the mounting bracket in place.

Filament Guide (2)

  • 2 go into the back of the filament guide and are used to connect the filament guide to the filament guide mounting plate.
Step 2 - Ream Holes for Retaining Pins

Use a 2 mm (a 5/64th or #47 should also work) drill bit to ream the holes for the retaining pins at the back of the spool holder. It is recommended to use a hand-turned drill and not a power drill.

The retaining pins are thin, so it is best to try not to force them into the holes until they have been reamed out.

A 1/16th bit should work in a pinch if you do not have any of the other sizes. Use the bit to ream the hole slightly larger, being careful to check the fit as you go.

Step 3 - Assemble Spool Holder
  • Disassemble the original spool holder that came with your Ultimaker and remove the RFID reader.
  • Put the RFID reader into the bottom of the spool holder. Ensure it is set all the way in.
  • Tuck the RFID reader cord into the cord channel and out the bottom.
  • Slide the spool holder top down over the RFID reader taking care not to damage the reader.
  • If the top and bottom of the spool holder do not touch at the middle seam, do not force it. Take the spool holder back apart, look for any support material in the RFID channel. Ensure the spool holder printed to the proper dimensions (properly calibrated).
Step 4 - Glue Together Mounting Bracket Assembly

Glue the Back Separator, Cross Brace (optional), and Filament Guide Mounting Plate to the Mounting Bracket.

There are index holes that can be used to align the Back Separator and Filament Guide Mounting Plate. Use of these holes is optional, you can align the parts by eye.

To use the index holes, drill them out (by hand) with a drill bit slightly smaller than a piece of filament. For example, if you use Ultimaker filament, which is 2.85 mm, then use a 2.8 mm drill bit.

Place a short piece of filament into the hole (small pliers can assist with this), then cut off the filament just proud of the surface (leave about 1.5-2.0 mm sticking out).

Step 5 - Mount Filament Guide

Use 2 M3x8 screws and, optionally, 2 M3 washers to mount the Filament Guide to the Filament Guide Mounting Plate.

Step 6 - Mount and Final Assembly
  • Place the assembled spool holder onto the Ultimaker using the same technique used to mount the original spool holder.
  • Plug the RFID cord into the bottom of the UM.
  • Replace the RFID cover (that came with the UM).
  • Slide the Filament Guide and Mounting Bracket Assembly over the front of the spool holder.
  • Use an M3 screw to lock the Mounting Bracket into place.

title: Simple E3D Titan Carriage for Tevo Tarantula

description.text:
A super simple, no frills x-carriage to mount a stepper motor and Titan extruder to. It mounts to the x-axis just like the original carriage or the popular modular x-carriage. I designed it for use with my Tevo Tarantula, but it should work with any printer that uses 2040 or 2020 extrusion for the x -axis.

It's only about 6mm wider than the original carriage and is the exact width of the modular x-carriage so it doesn't eat into your maximum X distance too much.

Because the Titan holds the hotend off center, it does slightly throw off the home position of the nozzle. The mounting surface between the stepper motor and Titan is 2mm thick so the Titan installs perfectly with the shorter set of screws and no extra spacers.

The nozzle does not stick down past the bottom of the x-axis extrusion very far so when installing, you may want to add an extra washer to each of the rear wheels to tilt the whole carriage slightly forward.

description.text:
Traveling with a laptop and playing simulators is not a good mix and while I missed my HOTAS setup back home I thought of building a mini HOTAS I could easily take with me and not take up too much room yet still be easy to use. Connects with USB to computer and uses standard drivers, no extra drivers necessary.

So I gutted an old RC transmitter and combined its gimbals with trim pots, some switches and toggles. Everything is powered using a Leobodnar BU0836A 12-Bit Joystick Controller and matrix board. Very easy tro use and install. The CC between mounting holes is 40mm hence the name Mini HOTAS 40.

Parts needed:
2pcs gimbals CC40mm
8pcs 7mm momentary push switches
4pcs 3-way flip switches
6pcs 10x2mm rare earth magnets
6pcs M3 screws
6pcs M3 knurl nuts
1pcs USB-cable (A-connector and open ended), length depending on your need. For use with laptop I have only 60cm.
1pcs Rubber grommet suitable for USB cable
1pcs zip tie
1pcs BU0836A 12-Bit Joystick Controller: http://www.leobodnar.com/shop/index.php?main_page=product_info&cPath=94&products_id=219
1pcs BU0836A Break out Matrix board: http://www.leobodnar.com/shop/index.php?main_page=product_info&cPath=94&products_id=274

Note: I've also designed a larger version for CC45mm gimbals: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2569465

Step 1. Print the box.

Step 2. Mount the knurl nuts in place using a solder iron. Make it hot and let it melt into the correct position.

Step 3 (optional). If you want to make the box nice spend some time to sand and plaster it smooth before applying paint.

Step 4. Glue magnets to box and supports. I use CA-glue with accelerator

Step 5. Insert a USB cable through the center hole of the box and solder to the BU0836. I use a rubber grommet to reduce dirt coming into the box.

Step 6. Solder USB cable to BU0836.

Step 7. Solder the BU0836 cards.

Step 8. Attach controls; joystick gimbal, switches and pots to the lid.

Step 9. Solder cables to the controls, twist them to reduce interference and make sure they are longer then you need.

Step 10. Trim cables with some extra cm to spare if the BU0836 is on the center bottom of the box.

Step 11. Solder controls to the BU0836 cards.

Step 12. Position BU0826 card in the bottom center of the box and pull on the USB cable so you have a few cm spare cm inside the box and attach the zip tie between the BU0826 and rubber grommet where it'll work as a strain relief.

Step 13. Hot glue the BU0836 cards (two dabs on either side so it is easy to detach if necessary).

Step 14. Use M3 screws and attach lid to box.

Step 15. Setup as a standrad joystick inthe simulator of your choice! :)

title: Airsoft AEG M4 Updated Selector Plate (Fixes G&P;)

description.text:
G&P Airsoft M4 has a design flaw which causes constant problems switching between SEMI/FULL. Trigger will jam going into FULL. The problem is that the selector plate is too thin, and is bring pushed out by the sector gear bearing, which doesn't sit flush with the outside of the gearbox. This is a version 2 gearbox with 8mm bearings.

This is a new selector plate which is twice as thick as the original, with additional cutouts for the bearings. The thickness allows it to make contact with the inside of the receiver, so that it can't bend outwards under tension and slip off of the cutoff lever (the reason the FA mode jams).

Selector plate may fit other M4 brands, depending on receiver dimensions. Printed with auto supports, no raft, in FlashPrint. ABS, Temp 230, high resolution. The only supports are under the bearing cutouts, and beveled edge.

Be careful with the spring guide pin at the top, it's very small and fragile! Use a razor blade to carefully clean under it so the spring will slide over it. I have this installed in my M4 now and it works beautifully.

title: Raspberry Pi Touchscreen mount for Ormerod 2 printer

description.text:
I wanted to attach my Raspberry Pi and Raspberry Pi Touchscreen to my Ormerod 2.
To:

  1. Control the printer with the touch screen
  2. Have a camera watch the print, so I could watch remotely.

I designed little legs that screw into the touch screen, and then can screw onto the Z axis of the Ormerod, via t-nuts.
The 40mm versions are pictured. They work, but the extruder stepper cable might [edit 6/Oct: ...will get...] get stuck on them on tall prints.
I designed a 50mm long version to hold the screen further from the axis, which should [edit 6/Oct: it doesnt, just don't print <12cm] prevent the problem.

The camera is an official Raspberry Pi camera. t I'm able to remotely connect to it via https://elinux.org/RPi-Cam-Web-Interface
I used the 30 cm long cable from CPC to place the camera in a more useful position, so I'm able to monitor the progress of the print via any web browser connected to the same local network. I can then run and save the print, or if too late, remotely stop the print using the Ormerod web server.

The screen is fairly secure, and doesn't seem to have alter the angle of the z-axis.

I judge the project to be a success.

This bracket allows you to attach a cheap eBay laser (http://www.ebay.com/itm/112386250526) to the stock Anet A8 carriage for laser cutting. The fan port powers and controls the laser. Note: Inkspace .92 and newer changed how scaling works and has issue with Lokster's plugin. Use Inkspace .91 or older to have proper scale when lasering. Also, get some real laser glasses, the cheap onse that come with the linked laser do not do a sufficient job.

title: Peopoly Moai Calibration Test - Corner Posts

description.text:
Test the x-y spacing and z build accuracy. Test the drift by placing a right-angle (or t-square) against the two rings before removing from the build plate.

The posts are 4mm in diameter and are spaced 100mm apart. Measuring between edges of posts should approach 104mm on the exterior edges (100 + 2mm radius + 2mm radius).

Don't bother measuring from the support base. That dimension will vary as the build plate rises off the bottom at different rates due to different tensions on the tray-calibration bolts.

This is a lightning detector enclosure. The lightning detector is based on the AS3935 lightning sensor from embeddedadventures.com. All the other components are modules from eBay. The neopixel arc shows the lightning distance from blue sky to red overhead The 4 indicators show the SD card status, the GPS status, and lightning sensor noise and disturbance alerts.

The initial design had the lightning sensor inside the main enclosure, but the neopixels caused interference which rendered the lightning sensor deaf to lightning. The save was to move the lightning sensor to the pod sticking out the back. This fix requires some manual rework (drilling, etc) because I was too lazy to rework the original design.

Printed with eSun Silver PLA, which has a nice color and good structural integrity but printed lousy. The eSun Black PLA parts turned out great. Taulman t-glase was used for the clear parts.

The complete electrical schematic and Arduino code are included with this post, so you could build this since it's all parts that can be ordered online. However I would rate it as a difficult build.

Notes: A high quality 5V 1A power supply is required because cheap switching power supplies interfere with the lightning sensor. Locate the device somewhere free of electrical noise (the indicator lights will glow red if there's too much interference). Power off when inserting the SD card.
